Quote: The front end of the log was carefully `sniped', that is, its sharp edge was rounded to allow it to skid like a sledge-runner.
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1986
Source: Speaking for Ourselves
Author: OWEN & PERKINS
Vol / Page: 159
Edition:
Quote: First of all they tapered one end, rounding the log so that it would be able to slide over impediments in its path, because it had to be dragged along the ground. Now these men were called `snipers', and having sniped the log, they then made two cuts, one on each side of the log opposite each other, right into the rounded part - the sniped end. That was for the purpose of holding a heavy chain which attached the log to the yoked bullocks ...
Notes: (Joe Gasparich, Northland kauri country)
